description.plain:
The first single from Pratt’s third record, Quiet Signs, her first wholly conceived in a professional studio setting, ups the ante on the kind of ethereal folk she explored pastoral moods with all over its predecessor, On Your Own Love Again, in 2015.

Though instead of the bedroom-pop tape hiss and soft psychedelia of the former, here we see the budding artist paint a crystalline 60s-tinged lounge crooner vision with just a handful of classical-strum finger-sweeps and a distant horn lull of some of her darkest fears in a kind of cathartic attempt to diffuse them.

body.plain:
Jessica Pratt makes peace with love that didn’t work out and reminds herself that she cannot go back to the rain (tragic joy and beautiful pain).

http://pitchfork.com/reviews/tracks/17205-jessica-pratt-back-baby/

annotations: And sometimes I pray for the rain

Here Jessica may be insinuating that she prays to experience that pain again, to go through it all over again just to have the moments with her loved one before that pain is to happen. Sounds counterintuitive but many people stay with someone even if painful just because they love that person so much. But she follows saying she can’t go back because she knows she has a responsibility to love herself enough this time to move on

That I generate a new design
 For the missing piece I had to disguise
Jessica’s saying: “May the rain I pray for – which will take me back to the time before our relationship was lost – generate the exact new element that was required to revitalise our love.”

Jessica did not know where to begin with ‘seeing things from [her partner’s] side’. This is because he was so keen to ‘leave things undefined’ that all meaning had departed from any relationship they had.

You know I try, to see things from your side
 To leave things undefined

These were the issues in Jessica’s failed relationship. A disagreement – despite attempts at empathy on Jessica’s part (‘see things from your side’). As well as another partner’s desire to perhaps have an open relationship (‘leave things undefined’).
Sometimes I pray for the rain

Jessica’s key wish. She prays for the rain because this metaphorical precipitation would melt the metaphorical ice which has metaphorically frozen time. In other words, if Jessica’s ‘prayer’ was answered, she’d be able to go back in time and rescue her broken relationship.

Look so lovely but you’ll have to decide
 If you could play it in reverse then you’d find
 That you’d better reconsider all the love you took and then cast aside

Pratt asks herself a magical question, “If you could, would you toss out all the joy of love for all the pain it later caused?” Pratt will soon return to reality reminding herself that she can’t go back. This is how humans grieve oscillating between magical questions and reality.
You and your glass world that does ring

Here are the two mysterious metaphors at the heart of the song: glass and rain.

One interpretation of these two metaphors.
– Glass is time.
– Rain is the bittersweet heartbreak and tragic heartbreak that Pratt is making peace with.

description.plain:
“Greycedes” is the fourth track from Jessica Pratt’s sophomore album, On Your Own Love Again.  Tracks such as this one have drawn comparisons to famous female singer-songwriters including Joni Mitchell and Joan Baez, though Pratt voiced her disagreement with these comparisons in an interview with Fader:

I don’t like the comparison of Joan Baez just because I don’t really like Joan Baez. I think she’s an incredible guitar player, and I understand her place in music history, but I don’t think [my music is a] purely folky thing. There was one man who was talking about it almost as if it was purely traditional old-school folk, like just Joni and Joan Baez, which is really not what I’m going for.
